jasthan-after-couple-2-year-old-test-positive-for-coronavirus-1657192-2020-03-19|title=Section 144 imposed in Rajasthan after couple, 2-year-old test positive for coronavirus|last=Parihar|first=Rohit|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Sikkim]]\n|style=\"background: #ccffcc;  |No\n| style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n| style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/east-and-northeast/sikkim-to-be-under-lockdown-from-6-am-on-march-25-till-march-31-817113.html|title=Sikkim to be under lockdown from 6 am on March 25 till March 31|date=2020-03-24|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tamil Nadu]]\n| style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |24 March\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n|style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n|<ref name=\"TNlockdown\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-tamil-nadu-to-go-under-lockdown-from-tuesday-1658800-2020-03-23|title=Coronavirus in India: Tamil Nadu to go under lockdown from Tuesday|last=ChennaiMarch 23|first=Shalini Lobo|last2=March 23|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|last3=Ist|first3=2020 19:18}}</ref><ref name=\"TNNtamilnadu\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Telangana]]\n|style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |23 March\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #ccffcc;\"  |No\n|<ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" /><ref name=\"TGcurfew\"/>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tripura]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n|style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n|<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|{{Partial}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n|style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n|<ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Uttarakhand]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #ccffcc;\" | No\n| <ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" />\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[West Bengal]]\n\n|style=\"background: #ffcccc;\" |Yes\n| <ref name=\"ITlockdown\" /><ref name=\"HTlockdown\" /><ref name=\"WB Lockdown\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/entire-west-bengal-brought-under-lockdown-till-march-31/articleshow/74792486.cms?from=mdr|title=Entire West Bengal brought under lockdown till March 31|date=2020-03-24|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:left;\" |'''Notes'''{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n|}\n\n== Andhra Pradesh ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2020}}\n'''On 23 March,''' Collector of Nellore district of [[Andhra Pradesh]] has imposed Section 144 in the district till March 31.\n\n== Chandigarh ==\n'''On 23 March,''' [[Punjab]] [[Governor (India)|Governor]] [[V. P. Singh Badnore]] who is also [[union territory]] [[Administrator of the government|administrator]] imposed a curfew starting midnight of 24 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.tribuneindia.com/news/coronavirus-curfew-in-chandigarh-from-midnight-60055|title=Coronavirus: Curfew to be imposed in Chandigarh from midnight|date=|work=The Tribune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Delhi ==\n'''On 5 March,''' [[Government of Delhi]] announced closure of all primary schools across Delhi 31 March as a precaution.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html|title=Coronavirus threat: Delhi govt orders closure of all primary schools till March 31|work=Hindustan Times|accessdate=5 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306042604/https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/coronavirus-threat-delhi-govt-orders-closure-of-all-primary-schools-till-march-31/story-ExewEmJeLCZ6egWDW6Ss2N.html|archive-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''On 12 March,''' it announced closure of schools, colleges and cinema halls till the end of March and ordered disinfection of all public places as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/schools-colleges-movie-theatres-to-be-shut-in-delhi-till-march-31-due-to-coronavirus-2193840|title=Delhi Schools, Colleges, Cinemas Shut Till March 31 Due To Coronavirus|date=12 March 2020|editor-last=Sanyal|editor-first=Anindita|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''On 22 March,''' after the central government's decision, complete lockdown of the Delhi from 6 am of 23 March to at least 31 March was declared. Essential services and commodities to continue.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jagannath|first1=J.|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/delhi-lockdown-to-start-at-6-am-monday-until-31-march-kejriwal-11584881955813.html|title=Delhi lockdown to start at 6 am Monday, until 31 March: Kejriwal|date=22 March 2020|work=Livemint|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''On 28 March,''' Delhi government had set up over 500 hunger relief camps providing free food for people who have been left stranded due to the nationwide lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/coronavirus-delhi-govt-sets-up-500-hunger-relief-camps/articleshow/74858737.cms|title=Coronavirus: Delhi govt sets up 500+ hunger relief camps {{!}} India News - Times of India|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Gujarat ==\n'''On 23 March,''' Gujarat DGP Shivanand Jha said that from 12 am, the entire state will be under lockdown till 31 March. \"State borders have been sealed. Action will be taken against the people who will violate the lockdown,\" he said.\n\n== Haryana ==\nOn 24 March, [[Government of Haryana]] announced complete lockdown of the Haryana.\n\n== Himachal Pradesh ==\nOn March 24, [[Government of Himachal Pradesh]] imposed an indefinite statewide curfew to combat coronavirus after it was found that many people defied the lockdown orders.\n\nChief minister [[Jai Ram Thakur]] said that the curfew will come into force in all 12 districts of the hill state at 5 pm on Tuesday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-indefinite-curfew-in-himachal-pradesh/articleshow/74792276.cms|title=Covid-19: Himachal imposes statewide curfew as people defy lockdown orders|date=24 March 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref>\n\n== Karnataka ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Karnataka#Governmental actions}}On 13 March, the [[Government of Karnataka]] ordered the closure of malls, universities and colleges, movie theatres, night clubs, marriages and conferences and other public areas as a precautionary measure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-karnataka-shuts-down-schools-malls-theatres-for-a-week-11584099614638.html|title=Coronavirus: Karnataka shuts down schools, malls, theatres for a week|website=livemint.com|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nKarnataka has closed its borders with Kerala for vehicular traffic in the wake of six people testing positive for coronavirus in Kasargod district of Kerala, which lies on the border of [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/21/karnataka-closes-border-with-kerala-after-6-covid-19-cases-reported-in-kasargod.html|title=Karnataka closes border with Kerala after 6 COVID-19 cases reported in Kasargod|date=21 March 2020|newspaper=The Week}}</ref>\n\n== Kerala ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Kerala#Governmental actions}}The [[Government of Kerala]] had declared high alert from 4 to 8 February and then again starting 8 March 2020 due to coronavirus cases being reported in the state.<ref name=\"ecfeb8\">{{cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-over-3000-people-still-under-observation-says-govt/articleshow/74034608.cms|title=Coronavirus: Over 3000 people still under observation, says govt|date=8 February 2020|work=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref name=\"gulfnews\">{{cite news|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/as-coronavirus-cases-surge-kerala-put-on-high-alert-1.1583752066135|title=As coronavirus cases surge, Kerala put on high alert|work=gulfnews.com|accessdate=9 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the government of Kerala shut down all colleges and schools up to grade 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/health/coronavirus-six-fresh-cases-reported-in-kerala-schools-colleges-cinemas-shut-till-march-31/1894165/|title=Coronavirus: Six fresh cases reported in Kerala; Schools, colleges, cinemas shut till March 31|date=10 March 2020|website=The Financial Express|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> The government had also urged people to not undertake pilgrimages, attend large gatherings such as weddings and cinema shows.<ref name=\"mar10\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/12-coronavirus-cases-kerala-grandparents-family-italy-test-positive-119892|title=12 coronavirus cases in Kerala, grandparents of family from Italy test positive|work=thenewsminute.com|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a new initiative 'Break the Chain' aiming to educate people about the importance of public and personal hygiene was introduced by Government of Kerala.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ndtv.com/kerala-news/kerala-launches-break-the-chain-campaign-to-combat-coronavirus-2196103%3famp=1&akamai-rum=off|title=Kerala govt launches break the chain initiative for personal hygiene|work=NDTV|accessdate=15 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Madhya Pradesh ==\nOn 25th Jan, the [[Government of Madhya Pradesh|Madhya Pradesh Government]] issued an advisory regarding Coronavirus symptoms and possibility of human to human transmission and ordered that all health professionals be educated about the same.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.mp.gov.in/sites/default/files/2020-03/69-25-1-2020.pdf|title=Advisory for Novel Coronavirus spread Control and Prevention|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 28th Jan, government issued notification to start testing people at the airport coming from China, Japan and Thailand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.mp.gov.in/sites/default/files/2020-03/75-28-1-2020.pdf|title=Notification to initiate health check-up for international passengers with respect to Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Following declaration by WHO of Coronavirus as Public Health Emergency on International concern, the government moved to monitor and test people coming from China and other affected countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.mp.gov.in/sites/default/files/2020-03/81-31-1-2020.pdf|title=Update on prevention and cure on Novel Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.mp.gov.in/sites/default/files/2020-03/79-30-1-2020.pdf|title=MP Government order regarding Monitoring of Coronavirus|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.health.mp.gov.in/sites/default/files/2020-03/91-4-2-2020.pdf|title=MP Government notification regarding monitoring of passengers coming from China|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March, all schools and cinemas in the state were shut down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-schools-cinema-halls-closed-in-madhya-pradesh-1655338-2020-03-14|title=Coronavirus: Schools, cinema halls closed in Madhya Pradesh|last=BhopalMarch 14|first=Press Trust of India|last2=March 14|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=2020 00:11}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the acting chief minister of state [[Kamal Nath]] ordered complete shutdown including all business establishments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/kamal-nath-instructs-complete-shut-down-in-mp-amid-corona-threat/articleshow/74764165.cms|title=Kamal Nath instructs complete shut down in MP amid corona threat {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Mar 22|first=Rajendra Sharma {{!}} TNN {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=23:12}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the government imposed curfew in Bhopal and Jabalpur cities where Coronavirus cases were found.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/covid-19-madhya-pradesh-govt-imposes-curfew-in-bhopal-jabalpur-817069.html|title=COVID-19: Madhya Pradesh govt imposes curfew in Bhopal, Jabalpur|date=2020-03-24|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, CM Shivraj Singh Chauhan announced various welfare measures in view of the nationwide lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yadav|first=Sidharth|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/madhya-pradesh-govt-to-give-bpl-families-free-ration-for-a-month/article31168585.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Madhya Pradesh govt. to give BPL families free ration for a month|date=2020-03-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, total lockdown for 03 days including suspension of essential services was imposed in [[Indore district|Indore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/coronavirus-cases-in-mp-madhya-pradesh-news-and-updates/articleshow/74821979.cms|title=Madhya Pradesh reports third death due to coronavirus|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> With nearly 60% of the state's cases, Indore is fast becoming the epicenter for spread of coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/indore/indore-and-ujjain-hotspots-of-coronavirus-outbreak-in-madhya-pradesh-home-to-70-cases/articleshow/74893924.cms|title=Indore and Ujjain hotspots of coronavirus outbreak in Madhya Pradesh, home to 70% cases {{!}} Indore News - Times of India|last=Mar 30|first=TNN {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31|last3=Ist|first3=17:27}}</ref> This strict decision is being taken to bring things under control.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/north-and-central/madhya-pradesh-government-making-all-efforts-to-fight-coronavirus-cm-shivraj-singh-chouhan-819419.html|title=Madhya Pradesh government making all efforts to fight coronavirus: CM Shivraj Singh Chouhan|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 05 April, Bhopal became the second district in the state to go for a tougher lockdown like Indore. All shops except for medicine and milk will be shut down. This decision was taken after two top bureaucrats Principal Secretary Health Pallavi Jain Govil and Additional Director Information/Communication (Health) Dr Veena Sinha were tested positive for Covid-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-only-medicine-milk-to-be-available-as-bhopal-goes-for-tougher-lockdown-2206531|title=Only Medicine, Milk To Be Available As Bhopal Goes For Tougher Lockdown|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Maharashtra ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maharashtra#Response and impact}}\n[[File:India Maharashtra COVID-19 map.svg|thumb|Map of districts with confirmed cases in Maharashtra]]\nOn 13 March, the [[Government of Maharashtra|Maharashtra Government]] declared the outbreak an [[epidemic]] in [[Mumbai]], [[Navi Mumbai]], [[Pune]], [[Pimpri-Chinchwad]] and [[Nagpur]], and invoked provisions of [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/maharashtra-invokes-epidemic-act-55079|title=Maharashtra invokes epidemic Act|work=The Tribune|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the Federation of Trade Association of Pune announced that all shops, barring grocery stores and pharmacies, will be shut in the city, resulting in the closure of up to 40,000 shops.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/market/coronavirus-impact-markets-in-maharashtra-in-shutdownmode/1901557/|title=Coronavirus impact: Markets in Maharashtra in shutdown mode|work=Financial Express|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the state government announced the closure of workplaces, excluding essential services and public transport, in Mumbai, [[Mumbai Metropolitan Region]], Pune, Pimpri-Chinchwad and Nagpur until 31 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/mumbai-pune-offices-shops-to-close-in-wake-of-coronavirus-says-uddhav-thackeray-11584692833403.html|title=Mumbai, Pune offices to close in wake of coronavirus, says Uddhav Thackeray|work=Livemint|accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government declared that [[Section 144]] would be imposed across the state, with effect from 23 March, sending the state into a lockdown.<ref name=\"section144\" />\n\nOn 23 March, the [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Uddhav Thackeray]] announced the closure of borders of all districts and a strict statewide curfew.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/uddhav-thackeray-imposes-curfew-in-entire-maharashtra/articleshow/74775886.cms?from=mdr|title=Uddhav Thackeray imposes curfew in entire Maharashtra|date=2020-03-23|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Odisha ==\nThe government of Odisha has been credited with an early response to the pandemic. On 13 March, the chief minister Naveen Pantaik declared it as a 'disaster'. Educational institutions and other public places were closed and officials were empowered by invoking the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]].<ref>Ashutosh Mishra, [https://thewire.in/government/odisha-covid-19-response Early Response Has Been Key to Odisha's Efforts to Tackle COVID-19], The Wire, 28 March 2020.</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, after confirming two positive cases of coronavirus, the state ordered 70 per cent lockdown, including its capital Bhubaneshwar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/blog/health/covid-19-how-odisha-is-setting-an-example-in-preparedness-69940|title=COVID-19: How Odisha is setting an example in preparedness|last=|first=|date=|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the [[Government of Odisha|state government]] extended it to a complete lockdown until 9 pm of March 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-update-odisha-govt-announces-lockdown-till-29-march-11584865948737.html|title=Coronavirus update: Odisha govt announces lockdown till 29 March|last=|first=|date=2020-03-22|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Interstate bus services and passenger trains were also suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhubaneswar/coronavirus-odisha-government-suspends-inter-state-bus-services-forms-team-to-monitor-smooth-flow-of-essential-goods/articleshow/74762169.cms|title=Coronavirus: Odisha government suspends inter-state bus services; forms team to monitor smooth flow of essential goods {{!}} Bhubaneswar News - Times of India|last=bisoyi|first=Sujit kumar|date=|website=The Times of India|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe government on 26 March signed agreements with medical colleges to set up two 1,000-bed hospitals in Bhubaneswar for treatment of the infected patients within 15 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/worries-grow-in-odisha-after-3rd-coronavirus-case-state-plans-1000-bed-hospital-2552869.html|title=Worries Grow in Odisha After 3rd Coronavirus Case; State Plans 1,000-bed Hospital|last=|first=|date=|website=News18|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Punjab ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2020}}\nOn 13 March, the Punjab governments declared holidays in all schools and colleges till 31 March\n\nOn 16 March Punjab government issue an advisory to close gyms, restaurants, etc.\n\nOn 19 March Punjab School Education Board postponed all Board Exams of 10th and 12th classes.\n\n20 March Punjab government also shuts down public transport in state from midnight of 20 March and prohibited gathering of more than 20 persons.\n\nOn 22 March Punjab government declared complete Lockdown in state till 31 March 2020 except Emergency services along Kala Sanghian.\n\nOn 23 March Punjab Government imposed full curfew across Punjab without any relaxation, become first State to impose full curfew, as some people were defy to follow lockdown, seriously.[19] Punjab government sanctions 20 crore rupees for free food, medicines to poor from CM Relief Fund, ministers pledge month's salary for efforts to control COVID-19.\n\nOn 24 March Punjab Chief Minister set up COVID Relief Fund to be utilised for the welfare of the people in distress due to Coronavirus.\n\n== Rajasthan ==\nOn 19 March, Section 144 was imposed in Rajasthan after three of a family tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Iqbal|first=Mohammed|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/coronavirus-prohibitory-orders-in-rajasthan-after-3-new-cases-test-positive/article31105200.ece|title=Coronavirus {{!}} Prohibitory orders in Rajasthan after 3 new cases test positive|date=2020-03-19|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\"RJcurfew\" />\n\nOn 22 March, the [[Government of Rajasthan]] banned public transport services in the state.<ref name=\"RJban\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-update-rajasthan-bans-private-vehicles-to-give-pension-food-to-poor/story-McqrXsvPuqHPEA7wTe6qDI.html|title=Coronavirus update: Rajasthan bans private vehicles; to give pension, food to poor|last=|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, the state banned all private vehicles in the roads after COVID-19 cases crossed 32 in the state.<ref name=\"RJban\" /> The state government had also announced free ration for two months for families covered under the National Food Security Act (NFSA).<ref name=\"RJban\" />\n\n== Tamil Nadu ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tamil Nadu#Governmental response}}\nOn 30 January,  the state had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=B. S.|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the [[Government of Tamil Nadu]] partially closed its borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the state government postponed the Class 10 SSLC board exams to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news |title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu\u2019s Class 10 board exams postponed |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government extended 'Janata curfew' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the state government imposed Section 144 from March 24 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref name=\"TNNtamilnadu\" />\n\nOn 24 March, Health Minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]] announced a hospital dedicated for treating COVID-19 patients. The newly built Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital was being converted into a special facility with 350 beds to treat COVID-19 patients exclusively.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, the state government announced care package of Rs.1000 and ration of food supply for each households.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stopcoronatn.in/files/8496PDIPR-P.R.No.249-TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020.pdf|title=TNPDS-PressRelease-Date02.04.2020|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Telangana ==\nOn 17 March, [[Government of Telangana]] started implementing screening of people entering Telangana from Maharashtra at four entry points.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/restrictions-on-maha-border-extended-by-t/articleshow/74663674.cms|title=Restrictions on Maha border extended by T|work=Times of India|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the state government announced a state-wide lockdown as five more cases emerged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/covid-19-telangana-goes-under-lockdown-as-five-more-positive-cases-emerge-11584890868818.html|title=Covid-19: Telangana goes under lockdown as five more positive cases emerge|last=Lasania|first=Yunus Y.|date=2020-03-22|website=Livemint|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the state government imposed night curfew from 7 pm till 6 am.<ref name=\"TGcurfew\">{{Cite web|url=https://newsmeter.in/telangana-government-imposes-strict-night-curfew-violators-to-be-dealt-strictly/|title=Telangana government imposes strict night curfew, violators to be dealt strictly|last=Network|first=Newsmeter|date=2020-03-23|website=NewsMeter|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> During the lockdown, no vehicles were not allowed on the roads. The government has also closed all borders and suspended interstate transport.<ref name=\"TGcurfew\" />\n\n== Uttar Pradesh ==\n{{Main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Uttar Pradesh#Response}}\nCM [[Yogi Adityanath]] announced on 21 March that the Uttar Pradesh government has decided to give \u20b91,000 (US$14) to all daily wage laborers affected due to coronavirus in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/covid-19-coronavirus-uttar-pradesh-yogi-adityanath-1658075-2020-03-21|title=Covid-19: UP CM Yogi Adityanath says daily wage workers to get Rs 1,000 per day|last=LucknowMarch 21|first=India Today Web Desk|last2=March 21|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|last3=Ist|first3=2020 10:40}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Chief Minister [[Yogi Adityanath]] announced the lockdown of fifteen districts in state, from 22 to 25 March, including [[Noida]], [[Ghaziabad]], [[Agra]], [[Aligarh]], [[Prayagraj district|Prayagraj]], [[Kanpur]], [[Varanasi]], [[Bareilly]], Lucknow, [[Saharanpur]], [[Meerut]], [[Lakhimpur]], [[Azamgarh]], [[Gorakhpur]] and others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-up-cm-yogi-adityanath-announces-lockdown-districts-1658470-2020-03-22|title=Coronavirus in India: UP CM Yogi Adityanath announces lockdown in 15 districts|last=DelhiMarch 22|first=India Today Web Desk New|last2=March 22|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29|last3=Ist|first3=2020 21:23}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, the [[Government of Uttar Pradesh|Uttar Pradesh government]] deployed 1000 [[Uttar Pradesh State Road Transport Corporation|UPSRTC]] buses to ferry migrant workers to their native districts during the nationwide lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/nation/2020/mar/28/up-govt-deploys-1000-upsrtc-buses-to-ferry-migrants-to-respective-districts-2122705.html|title=UP govt deploys 1000 UPSRTC buses to ferry migrants to respective districts|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n== West Bengal ==\nOn 23 March, starting 5 PM, [[Kolkata]] and several areas across [[West Bengal]] were put under a lockdown till 27 March.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/kolkata-several-areas-across-west-bengal-to-be-under-lockdown-from-monday-evening-to-march-27-2546569.html|title=Kolkata, Several Areas Across West Bengal to be Under Lockdown From Monday Evening to March 27|date=|work=News18|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, starting 5 PM, entire state of [[West Bengal]] was put under a lockdown till 31 March.<ref name=\"WB Lockdown\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n*[[2020 India coronavirus lockdown]]\n*[[Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian state government responses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Current event|2=current pandemic|date=March 2020}}\nThe Indian state governments have responded to the '''[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India|2020 coronavirus pandemic India]]''' with various declarations of emergency, closure of institutions and public meeting places, and other restrictions intended to contain the spread of the virus.\n\n{{horizontal TOC|align=center|nonum=yes}}\n\n== State level regulations (before 24 March) ==\nThe table lists state level regulations that were imposed by the respective state and central governments before 24 March 2020. On 24 March, Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] ordered a [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown|nationwide lockdown]] from 12:01 am of 25 March for three weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gettleman|first=Jeffrey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/24/world/asia/india-coronavirus-lockdown.html|title=Modi Orders 3-Week Total Lockdown for All 1.3 Billion Indians|date=2020-03-24|work=The New 